1. What is JUnit and what are its features?
JUnit is a popular Java testing framework used for writing and running unit tests.
Features:
•	Supports automated testing 
•	Provides annotations for test structure 
•	Assertions to validate results 
•	Test runners to execute tests 
•	Integration with build tools like Maven & Gradle 
•	Supports parameterized tests (JUnit 5) 
________________________________________
2. Important annotations in JUnit
•	@Test – marks a test method 
•	@BeforeEach – runs before each test 
•	@AfterEach – runs after each test 
•	@BeforeAll – runs once before all tests 
•	@AfterAll – runs once after all tests 
•	@Disabled – skips a test 
•	@DisplayName – custom test name 
________________________________________
3. JUnit assert methods
Used to validate expected results:
•	assertEquals(expected, actual) 
•	assertNotEquals() 
•	assertTrue(), assertFalse() 
•	assertNull(), assertNotNull() 
•	assertThrows() (JUnit 5) 
________________________________________
4. Difference between JUnit 4 and JUnit 5
•	JUnit 5 is modular (JUnit Platform, Jupiter, Vintage) 
•	Better annotations (@BeforeEach instead of @Before) 
•	Supports lambda expressions 
•	Improved assertions and extensions 
•	More flexible and extensible than JUnit 4 
________________________________________
5. Testing exceptions in JUnit 5
Use assertThrows():
assertThrows(ArithmeticException.class, () -> {
    int result = 10 / 0;
});
It verifies that a specific exception is thrown.
________________________________________
6. What is JaCoCo and why is it used?
JaCoCo is a code coverage tool for Java.
Used for:
•	Measuring test coverage 
•	Identifying untested code 
•	Improving code quality 
________________________________________
7. Generate and run JaCoCo report
Steps:
1.	Add JaCoCo plugin in Maven/Gradle 
2.	Run tests (mvn test) 
3.	Generate report (mvn jacoco:report) 
4.	View report in target/site/jacoco/index.html 
________________________________________
8. Improve code coverage using JaCoCo
•	Write more unit tests 
•	Cover edge cases and exceptions 
•	Test all branches and conditions 
•	Use integration tests 
•	Refactor complex code 
