9. Define Docker and key features
Docker is a containerization platform to package applications with dependencies.
Features:
•	Lightweight containers 
•	Fast deployment 
•	Portability 
•	Isolation 
•	Version control via images 
________________________________________
10. Docker images, Dockerfile, Docker Hub
•	Docker Image: Read-only template for containers 
•	Dockerfile: Script to build images 
•	Docker Hub: Online repository for storing images 
________________________________________
11. Lifecycle of a Docker container
•	Create → Start → Run → Pause → Stop → Remove
Containers move through these stages during execution. 
________________________________________
12. Key components of Docker architecture
•	Docker Client 
•	Docker Daemon 
•	Docker Images 
•	Docker Containers 
•	Docker Registry (Docker Hub) 
________________________________________
13. Virtualization vs Containerization
•	Virtualization uses VMs with full OS 
•	Containerization shares host OS 
•	Containers are lightweight and faster 
•	VMs are heavier but more isolated 
________________________________________
14. Start, stop, kill Docker container
•	Start: docker start <id> 
•	Stop: docker stop <id> 
•	Kill: docker kill <id> (force stop) 
________________________________________
15. Purpose of volume in Docker run
Volumes are used to:
•	Persist data outside containers 
•	Share data between containers 
•	Avoid data loss when container stops 
________________________________________
16. Why multiple deployment systems?
They address:
•	Scalability issues 
•	Environment differences 
•	Continuous deployment needs 
•	Automation challenges 
________________________________________
17. What is virtualization and components?
Virtualization creates virtual machines on a physical system.
Components:
•	Hypervisor 
•	Virtual Machines 
•	Host OS 
•	Guest OS 
________________________________________
18. Client vs server-side execution
•	Client-side runs on user's browser (JavaScript) 
•	Server-side runs on server (Java, Python) 
•	Client-side is faster for UI 
•	Server-side handles logic & security 
________________________________________
19. What is Puppet and its working?
Puppet is a configuration management tool.
•	Puppet Master: controls configurations 
•	Puppet Agent: applies configurations
Agents communicate with master to maintain system state. 
________________________________________
20. Benefits of Puppet
•	Automation 
•	Consistency 
•	Scalability 
•	Faster deployments 
•	Reduced manual errors 
